December 1st in 1713 Bach travelled to Halle as an organ construction consultant and the church paid all of his expenses, which for two weeks included 18 groschen for beer only. That would equal 32 quarts/30 liters of beer. Equals 4-5 pints per day. On top, 8 groschen for brandy.

When Arthur Jones was travelling around looking for work as a very young man, he said he would go to small town police stations and ask if they had a free bed for him, basically arrest him for a night so he didn't have to sleep outside. They gave him breakfast in the morning too.

After a few years he was friends with all small town police chiefs and the policemen. They never refused to house him for the night if there was a free bed, guess they were happy they could actually help someone stay out of trouble voluntarily. Better than a hotel. Life in 1930s.

It's insane that some people have a desire to "meet new people"

Like some people genuinely go to bars or try to join like sports hobby leagues or whatever due to a desire to willingly introduce themselves to other people and voluntarily "make new friends". It's both endearing and puzzling to me.
I guess you do need a few good people to rely on in that case but for many it seems to be a sort of pathological compulsion for social novelty

I guess some people feel more loneliness than others and it's always preferable to have a few good people to be able to rely on, if you "have no one" it's justifiable to seek others in any way, but outside of that this seems to express some compulsion for perpetual social novelty
